{"/service/ndnp/iahi/batch_iahi_jackson_ver01/data/sn86061215/00415668764/1907112601/0488.xml":{"full_text":"DAVENPORTS,\nCHINA CABINETS,\nFOLDING BED8,\nMISSION CLOCKS,\nMAGAZINE STANDS,\nCHILDREN ROCKER8,\nKITCHEN CABINETS,\nLIBRARY TABLE8,\nCHIFFIONERS,\nHALL RACKS,\nRESOLUTIONS.\nAgency.\u2014The following resolution\nwere adopted by Gen. E. F. Wlnslov\npost, No. 107, department of Iowa,\nGrand lodge of the Republic:\nWhereas our esteemed comrade in\narms, Isaac McKowen, who has been\ncalled by the Supreme commander, to\nlay his earthly armor down, and enter\nthe \"gates ajar,\" to the portals of that\ninnumeral company, the Eternal\nGrand Army above, whose Borrow af\nfliction and death of Father McKowen\nWinslow post has lost a valued mem\nber, the community an honored citizen\nand that we extend to the daughters\nand relatives our fraternal sincere\nsympathy:\nResolved That our charter be drap\ned in mourning for the space of thirty\ndays and that these resolutions be\nrecorded in our book of records and a\ncopy be presented to the relatives of\nour deceased comrade, also a copy\nbe Sent the Ottumwa Courier for publi\ncation. Committee: John Dwire, J. C.\nHawkin,s S. V. Sampson.\nTailor made suits at just half. Done\nlan's.\nW. H. Cooper S: Son\nChristmas Suggestions\nAt this season of the year a great many people are\npondering on what to buy that will make a suitable\nChristmas gift for some relative or friend\u2014\nLET US HELP YOU TO DECIDE\nOur store at present is filled with hundreds of useful\nand beautiful articles for this occasion.\nLook This List Over Carefully\nMUSIC CABINET8,\nBOOK TROUGHS,\nSHAVING 8TAND8,\n8M0KING CABINETS,.\nFANCY JARDINER8,\nPARLOR CABINETS,\nLADIES' DESKS,\nPLUSH ROPE PORTIERS,\nFANCY CANDLESTICK8,\nDIVANS,\nThen come in and make your selection and have it laid away\nfor you. Telephone your instructions for delivery\u2014we do the rest.\nW. H. Cooper Son\nEASY PAYMENTS EASY PAYMENTS\nWe pay Railroad Fare according to the Rules of the\nRetail Merchants' Association\nSTOCKPORT.\nStockport.\u2014H. T. Morris and his\ndaughter-in-law, Pearl Morris and\nchildren, left Saturday evening for\nChicago to visit his eon, S. M. Morris.\nEli Terneham came in Saturday\nevening from Cooperstown, Dakota.\nHe reports that the money stringency\nhas had a depressing effect on busi\nness up there.\nThe Freewill Baptists of Utica came\nup Thursday and Baptized twenty\nsevtn In the baptistry of the Christian\nchurch, the results of a protracted\nmeeting held by an evangelist from\nIllinois.\nMr. and Mrs. B. F. Oldt entertained\na few of their friends Sunday it being\nthe thirty-second anniversary of their\nwedding.\nMr. Mathtews* father of LaCrew\nvisited over Sunday with him at\nStockport.\nDick Workman arrived here Satur\nday morning from Wyoming, with a\ncar load of horses.' One had the mis\nfortune to get down and was tramped\nto death.\nB&rve Fox and Marion Ashby left\nthis morning for Fort Madison, where\nthey expect to work in the round\nhouse of the Santa Fe railroad.\nMERCHANT FROM WHOM YOU TRADE WITH ON THE FOLLOWING SCALE:\nTOWNS FROM-\n5 to 15 Miles\n16 to 20 Miles0ne\nW. J. DONELAN CO.\nJ. E. SCASE DRY GOODS CO.\nJ. DYSART CLO CO\nPEACH CRESSWELL CLO. CO.\nDOTY CLO. CO.\nTHE HUB CLO. CO.\nJ. B. SAX, CLOTHIER.\nCELLARETTS,\nELECTRIC LAMPS,\nGA8 LAMPS,\nPICTURES,\nROCKERS,\nPEDESTALS,\nBOOK RACKS,\nRUG8,\nDRESSERS,\nCOUCHES.\nTIVE SECURITIES WERE LOST WITH NOT A SINGLE LEGITIMATE FAILURE\u2014TO CELEBRATE OUR PRESENT PROSPERITY\nTHE DIFFERENT MERCHANT'S ANNOUNCEMENTS OF THE SALE. TH UNDERSIGNED MERCHANTS\nFARES FOR ONE PERSON\u2014\nOne way with $10 purchase.\nBoth ways with $20 purchase.\nway wlth\n*1250\npurchase'\nBoth ways with $25 purcahse.\nPHILLIPS' BIG STORE.\nNELSON CLOAK CO.\nJ. W. NEASHAM, JEWELER.\nN. W. COWLES, JEWELER.\nKEATING HARDWARE CO.\nOTTUMWA HARDWARE CO.\nW. A. McINTIRE CO.\nEYES TESTED FREE by a gradu\nate Optician. Our prices for glasses\nare always reasonable.'\nARNOLD'S\nJEWELRY AND MUSIC STORE,\nOttumwa, Iowa.\nAMADOR.\nAmador.\u2014Mrs. John Laughead was\nthe guest of Mrs. Alex Martin Tues\nday.\nFred Hancock was in the county seat\nTuesday.\nMr. and Mrs. T. D. Williams visited\nat the home of Bert Miller Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. James Schwartz are\npreparing to move to Ottumwa this\nweek.\nIra Haning and wife were in town\nrecently.\nMr. and Mrs. T. Q. Wellman of Ot\ntumwa spent Sunday with the for\nmer's parents here.\nMr. and Mrs. Carl Schwartz enter-\nTOWNS FROM\u2014\nSTATE'S DOCKET\nIS NEAR CLOSE\nONLY TWO MORE CASES TO BE\nHEARD AND CRIMINAL\nCOURT ADJOURNS.\nOnly two state cases remain to be\ntried and then the crimnal docket will\nbe closed for this term of the circuit\ncourt. Several days will be required\nin which to dispose of these.\nThis forenoon the case against Ed\nward Stewart, colored, Indicted for\nlarceny from a building at night, was\ntaken up, being the third and last in\ndictment on the same charge. On the\nfirst a plea of guilty was entered to\nmere larceny and he was give thirty\ndays in the county jail. The second\nIndictment came up on Saturday and\nbecause the prosecuting witness was\nunable to identify a bicycle which\nformerly he had claimed had been\nstolen by Stewart, the county attorney\ndismissed the case.\nThe other case, is that of the state\nof Iowa against Charles Parker, in\ndicted for practicing medicine with\nout a license.\nGets Six Months.\nH. N. Townsend who last week\npleaded guilty to a serious statutory\noffense was sentenced by Judge Elch\nelberger on Saturday to six months\nin the county jail.\nIn the case of Harry L. Taylor who\nwas to have been sentenced on a lar\nceny conviction today, has another\nchance as the day of sentence was\npostponed until tomorrow and a mo\ntion for a new trial made.\nPrepare to be on hand early at the\n\"Big Five\" sale tomorrow. A great\nharvest of exceptional bargains. Done\nlan's.\ntalned Marion Smith and wife and\nBert Wilkinson and wife Sunday.\nHenry Renfrew and son returned\nfrom Wyoming recently.\nMr. and Mrs. Lewis Cosman visited\nMrs. E. Haning Sunday.\nA protracted meeting Is being con\nducted by Rev. Ed Hastings at Russell\nChapel this week.\nMrs, John Laughead visited in town\nlast week.\nMr. and Mrs. Loran Shields left to\nday for Colorado for a visit with Mrs.\nShields' parents and other relatives.\nBeginning tomorrow Donelan's will\nclose out their entire remaining stock\nof stylish tailor made suits at exact\nly half price.\nThe Difference\nBetween living well and living poor\nly Is very small if you buy right. The\nfellow who knows it all Is satisfied,\nbut people who are seeking new Ideas\nare wlllling to learn. We invite you\nto call on us and let us show you how\nto buy Spectacles. There's only one\nglass that will fit your eye properly\nand If you don't get that one glass,\nyour eye is liable to be injured.\nWe fit each eye w:ith the proper\nlens and at the proper price.\nLet Us Examine Your Eyes\nIt's Free\nGraduate Optlclon in charge of Op\ntical department.\nArnold's\nJewelry Music \"Store\n113 East Main Street\nOttumwa-The Pride of Our Great State\nThe Greatest Trading Center in Iowa.\n31 to 45 Miles\nHUFFMAN CO., DRY GOODS.\nJ. H. CREMER, FUEL and FEED.\nHARPER\u2014McINTIRE CO.\n1-IALL-EKFELT FURNITURE CO\nDANIEL'S SHOE CO.\nSTEVEN'S SHOE CO.\nCLARK'S DRUG STORE.\nTHE ONLY CITY IN THE STATE WHOSE BANKS PROMPTLY MET AND PAID ALL CHECKS, THE ONLY CITY IN THE STATE WHOSE BANKS DID NOT ISSUE CLEARING HOUSE CERTIFICATES OR TAKE ADVANTAGE OF THE TIME\nLIMIT. THE ONLY CITY IN THE STATE THAT NEV&R HAD A BANK FAILURE IN FACT Ii IS SO LONG SINCE ANY BUSINESS HOUSE FAILED THAT WE CAN NOT CALL O MIND A SINGLE INCIDENT. TO CELEBRA1 THE RETURN OF\nPROSPERITY AFTER THE FEW DAYS OF MONEY STRINGENCY IN NEW YORK, WHEN COPPER STOCK, RAILROAD STOCK AND HUNDRED8 OF OTHER WATERED STOCK8 FELL WITH A CRA8H, WHEN F0RTUNE8 INVESTED IN SPECULA\u00ad\nThe Ottumwa Merchants Will Each Pat on a Great Sale\nEVERY ...ERCHANT VIEING WITH EACH OTHER TO SEE WHICH WILL GIVE THE GREATEST VALUES, SOME MERCHANTS BEING COMPELLED BY THE ARRIVAL OF CHRISTMAS GOOu^ TO SACRIFICE PART OF THEIR 8TOCK8 IN OR\u00ad\nDER TO MAKE QUICK SALES AND THUS MAKE ROOM FOR THEIR HOLIDAY GOODS. THIS IS THE WEEK YOU SHOULD COME TO OTTUMWA TO GET THE GREATEST VALUES OF THE YEAR. WATCH EVERY ISSUE OF THE COURIER FOR\nWill Pay Railroad Fare as Per the Following Rules\nWHEN PURCHASING YOUR TICKET GET A RECEIPT FOR SAME FROM THE TICKET AGENT AND PRESENT SAME TO THu. FIRST MERCHANT FROM WHOM YOU MAKE A PURCHASE. ALL FARES REFUNDED IN CASH BY THE LAST\nThe Ful Amount Specified Must be Purchased or No Fares Will be Paid.\n1 to 30 Miles\nmJ\nFARES FOR ONE PERSON-\nOne way with $15 purchase.\nBoth ways with $30 purchase.\nOne way with $20 purchase.\nBoth ways with $40 purchase.\nACQUITTAL FOR\nW, D. STEVENS\nMAN INDICTED FOR ATTEMPTED\n'ASSAULT ALLOWED HIS\nLIBERTY.\nAfter being out but thirty mlnutea\nand at the conclusion of the third\nballot the jury in the W. D. Stevens\ncase returned a verdict of not guilty\nto the indictment of assault with\ncriminal intent\nThree Ballots.\nOn the first ballot the jury stood\nten for acquittal, one for conviction\nand one blank. The next ballot stood\neleven to one and the third ballot\nwas unanimous for acquittal. Court\nhad adjourned when the case was\ngiven to the jury at 4:30 which\ncaused some delay and the verdict\nwas not returned Into court until\nnearly o'clock after some delay had\nbeen occassioned in getting the at\ntorneys to the court. house. Stevens\nwas ordered released from custody\nand he went home for the first time\nin several weeks since his arrest\nfor the crime of attempting to crim\ninally assault Miss Jeanette Yates,\nwhile on her way to her work at the\nOttumwa telephone company's ex\nchange on Second street.\nProved An Alibi.\nThe jury said by their verdicts that\nthe wrong man was accused of the\noffense. The girl positively indenti\nfled \"Steve\" as the man, but there\nwas no corroborative evidence such as\nis required in such cases. The de\nfense also established a perfect alibi\nthat he was at home in bed at the\ntime the crime was committed. The\nprosecution was not able to produce\na single witness to break the alibi.\nHerman Schmidt, who had testified\nfor the state in rebuttal that Stevens\nhad been in his place of business\nabout 8 o'clock, long enough to tele\nhone, was the nearest they came to\ndiscrediting the alibi.\nWhen the fact was simmered down\nMr. Schmidt did not know exactly\nwhat time it was that Stevens came\ninto his place but was sure it was\nabout 8 o'clock.\nThe Jury.\nThe jury was composed of the fol\nlowing:\nJohn Genochio, G. W. Giltner, M.\nS. Kirk, S. K. Alderice, Thomas\nBrown, C. A. Smith, Fred Rouch,\nEmery Sterling, F. M. Kelsey, Charles\nArgenbright, A. W. Melcher, A. P.\nThompson.\nStewart Case.\nToday the case of the state of Iowa\nvs. Ed Stewart, colored, indicted for\nstealing from a building 'at night, was\ntaken up. On one Indictment Stewart\nhad pleaded guilty and was sentenced\nto the county jail for thirty days.\nThere is one more indictment against\nhim.\nA few items from the \"Big Five\"\nsale at Donelan's\u2014Silk petticoats,\n$3.00. All wool blankets, $2.25 a pair.\nTaffeta silk and over lace waists\n$2.95. Good $5.00 Wilton velvet rugs\n$3.50. Splendid 50c beautiful em\nbroidered lisle hose 35c pair. Whol3\nstore full of bargains just like these.\nThe sale begins tomorrow.\nSeymour Eastern Stars at Centerville.\nSeymour.\u2014The Seymour chapter of\nthe Eastern Stair visited the Center'\nville chapter Tuesday evening. The in\nvitation was extended to six chapters,\nviz.: Moulton, Moravia, Mystic, Union\nville, Cincinnati and Seymour. Th\u00ab\nlargest delegation was from Seymour,\nthere being thirty-one visitors from\nthis chapter. The visitors were royal\nly entertained, and feel themselves\ndeeply Indebted to the Centerville\nchapter.\nLast Friday earning a deal 